# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hamiltonian-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] In Hamiltonian mechanics, a **canonical transformation** is a change of canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**) → (**Q**, **P**) that preserves the form of Hamilton's equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] This is sometimes known as *form invariance*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Although Hamilton's equations are preserved, it need not preserve the explicit form of the Hamiltonian itself.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Canonical transformations are useful in their own right, and also form the basis for the Hamilton–Jacobi equations (a useful method for calculating conserved quantities) and Liouville's theorem (itself the basis for classical statistical mechanics).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Therefore, coordinate transformations (also called *point transformations*) are a *type* of canonical transformation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] However, the class of canonical transformations is much broader, since the old generalized coordinates, momenta and even time may be combined to form the new generalized coordinates and momenta.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Canonical transformations that do not include the time explicitly are called *restricted canonical transformations* (many textbooks consider only this type).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Modern mathematical descriptions of canonical transformations are considered under the broader topic of symplectomorphism which covers the subject with advanced mathematical prerequisites such as cotangent bundles, exterior derivatives and symplectic manifolds.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The dot product (also known as an "inner product") maps the two coordinate lists into one variable representing a single numerical value.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The coordinates after transformation are similarly labelled with **Q** for transformed generalized coordinates and **P** for transformed generalized momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Restricted canonical transformations are coordinate transformations where transformed coordinates **Q** and **P** do not have explicit time dependence, i.e., ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} =\mathbf {Q} (\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {p} )}$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {P} =\mathbf {P} (\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {p} )}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] In general, a transformation (**q**, **p**) → (**Q**, **P**) does not preserve the form of Hamilton's equations but in the case of a time independent transformation some simplifications are possible.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] where it differs from the Hamiltonian by a partial time derivative of a function known as a generator, which reduces to being only a function of time for restricted canonical transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Although the class of canonical transformations is larger than that which can be obtained with this restricted formulation, the restricted version provides a good starting point to obtain results that can be further generalized.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] All of the following conditions, with the exception of bilinear invariance condition, can be generalized for the full class of canonical transformations, including time dependence.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] These are the **indirect conditions** to check whether a given transformation is canonical.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] where ${\textstyle \nabla _{\varepsilon }K=\nabla _{\varepsilon }H}$ can be used due to the form of Kamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The left hand side of the above is called the Poisson matrix of $\varepsilon$ , denoted as ${\textstyle {\mathcal {P}}(\varepsilon )=MJM^{T}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Similarly, a Lagrange matrix of $\eta$ can be constructed as ${\textstyle {\mathcal {L}}(\eta )=M^{T}JM}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] It can be shown that the symplectic condition is also equivalent to ${\textstyle M^{T}JM=J}$ by using the ${\textstyle J^{-1}=-J}$ property.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The set of all matrices ${\textstyle M}$ which satisfy symplectic conditions form a symplectic group.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The symplectic conditions are equivalent with indirect conditions as they both lead to the equation ${\textstyle {\dot {\varepsilon }}=J\nabla _{\varepsilon }H}$ , which is used in both of the derivations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The symplectic condition can also be recovered by taking ${\textstyle u=\varepsilon _{i}}$ and ${\textstyle v=\varepsilon _{j}}$ which shows that ${\textstyle (MJM^{T})_{ij}=J_{ij}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Thus these conditions are equivalent to symplectic conditions.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Furthermore, it can be seen that ${\textstyle {\mathcal {P}}_{ij}(\varepsilon )=\{\varepsilon _{i},\varepsilon _{j}\}_{\eta }=(MJM^{T})_{ij}}$ , which is also the result of explicitly calculating the matrix element by expanding it.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The symplectic condition can also be recovered by taking ${\textstyle u=\eta _{i}}$ and ${\textstyle v=\eta _{j}}$ which shows that ${\textstyle (M^{T}JM)_{ij}=J_{ij}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Furthermore, it can be seen that ${\textstyle {\mathcal {L}}_{ij}(\eta )=[\eta _{i},\eta _{j}]_{\varepsilon }=(M^{T}JM)_{ij}}$ , which is also the result of explicitly calculating the matrix element by expanding it.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] These set of conditions only apply to restricted canonical transformations or canonical transformations that are independent of time variable.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Note that the new coordinates need not be completely oriented in one coordinate momentum plane.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] If the above is obeyed for any arbitrary variations, it would be only possible if the indirect conditions are met.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The form of the equation, ${\textstyle {v}^{T}\,J\,w}$ is also known as a symplectic product of the vectors ${\textstyle {v}}$ and ${\textstyle w}$ and the bilinear invariance condition can be stated as a local conservation of the symplectic product.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Application of the **indirect conditions** above yields $\operatorname {det} (M)=1$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] To *guarantee* a valid transformation between (**q**, **p**, *H*) and (**Q**, **P**, *K*), we may resort to a direct **generating function** approach.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Both sets of variables must obey Hamilton's principle.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Lagrangians are not unique: one can always multiply by a constant λ and add a total time derivative ⁠*dG*/*dt*⁠ and yield the same equations of motion (as discussed on Wikibooks).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Here G is a generating function of one old canonical coordinate (**q** or **p**), one new canonical coordinate (**Q** or **P**) and (possibly) the time t.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Thus, there are four basic types of generating functions (although mixtures of these four types can exist), depending on the choice of variables.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] As will be shown below, the generating function will define a transformation from old to new canonical coordinates, and any such transformation (**q**, **p**) → (**Q**, **P**) is guaranteed to be canonical.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The type 1 generating function *G*1 depends only on the old and new generalized coordinates ${\textstyle G\equiv G_{1}(\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {Q} ,t)}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Ideally, one can invert these relations to obtain formulae for each *Qk* as a function of the old canonical coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of these formulae for the **Q** coordinates into the *second* set of N equations ${\textstyle \mathbf {P} =-{\frac {\partial G_{1}}{\partial \mathbf {Q} }}}$ yields analogous formulae for the new generalized momenta **P** in terms of the old canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] We then invert both sets of formulae to obtain the *old* canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**) as functions of the *new* canonical coordinates (**Q**, **P**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of the inverted formulae into the final equation ${\textstyle K=H+{\frac {\partial G_{1}}{\partial t}}}$ yields a formula for K as a function of the new canonical coordinates (**Q**, **P**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] In practice, this procedure is easier than it sounds, because the generating function is usually simple.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] For example, let ${\textstyle G_{1}\equiv \mathbf {q} \cdot \mathbf {Q} }$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] This example illustrates how independent the coordinates and momenta are in the Hamiltonian formulation; they are equivalent variables.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Ideally, one can invert these relations to obtain formulae for each *Pk* as a function of the old canonical coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of these formulae for the **P** coordinates into the *second* set of N equations ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} ={\frac {\partial G_{2}}{\partial \mathbf {P} }}}$ yields analogous formulae for the new generalized coordinates **Q** in terms of the old canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of the inverted formulae into the final equation ${\textstyle K=H+{\frac {\partial G_{2}}{\partial t}}}$ yields a formula for K as a function of the new canonical coordinates (**Q**, **P**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] For example, let ${\textstyle G_{2}\equiv \mathbf {g} (\mathbf {q} ;t)\cdot \mathbf {P} }$ where **g** is a set of N functions.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] This results in a point transformation of the generalized coordinates ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} ={\frac {\partial G_{2}}{\partial \mathbf {P} }}=\mathbf {g} (\mathbf {q} ;t)}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of these formulae for the **Q** coordinates into the *second* set of N equations ${\textstyle \mathbf {P} =-{\frac {\partial G_{3}}{\partial \mathbf {Q} }}}$ yields analogous formulae for the new generalized momenta **P** in terms of the old canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of the inverted formulae into the final equation ${\textstyle K=H+{\frac {\partial G_{3}}{\partial t}}}$ yields a formula for K as a function of the new canonical coordinates (**Q**, **P**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of these formulae for the **P** coordinates into the *second* set of N equations ${\textstyle \mathbf {Q} ={\frac {\partial G_{4}}{\partial \mathbf {P} }}}$ yields analogous formulae for the new generalized coordinates **Q** in terms of the old canonical coordinates (**q**, **p**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Substitution of the inverted formulae into the final equation ${\textstyle K=H+{\frac {\partial G_{4}}{\partial t}}}$ yields a formula for K as a function of the new canonical coordinates (**Q**, **P**).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] This process is possible when the matrix defined by ${\textstyle a_{ij}={\frac {\partial {p}_{i}(\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {P} )}{\partial P_{j}}}}$ is non-singular using the inverse function theorem, and can be restated as the following relation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] These conditions also correspond to local invertibility of the coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Hence, the canonical transformations resulting from these four generating functions alone are not completely general.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] However, as a feature of canonical transformations, it is always possible to choose 2*N* such independent functions from sets (**q**, **p**) or (**Q**, **P**), to form a generating function representation of canonical transformations, including the time variable.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Hence, it can be proven that every finite canonical transformation can be given as a closed but implicit form that is a variant of the given four simple forms.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] This step is equivalent to equating the left hand side as ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial (K-H)}{\partial P}}={\frac {\partial Q}{\partial t}}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Similarly the canonical transformation rules are obtained by equating the left hand side as ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial (K-H)}{\partial Q}}=-{\frac {\partial P}{\partial t}}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The canonical transformation relations are hence said to be equivalent to ${\textstyle J\left(\nabla _{\varepsilon }{\frac {\partial G}{\partial t}}\right)={\frac {\partial \varepsilon }{\partial t}}}$ in this context.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The analysis of restricted canonical transformations is hence consistent with this generalization.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Where the last terms of each equation cancel due to ${\textstyle J\left(\nabla _{\varepsilon }{\frac {\partial G}{\partial t}}\right)={\frac {\partial \varepsilon }{\partial t}}}$ condition from canonical transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Hence leaving the symplectic relation: ${\textstyle MJM^{T}=J}$ which is also equivalent with the condition ${\textstyle M^{T}JM=J}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] It follows from the above two equations that the symplectic condition implies the equation ${\textstyle J\left(\nabla _{\varepsilon }{\frac {\partial G}{\partial t}}\right)={\frac {\partial \varepsilon }{\partial t}}}$ , from which the indirect conditions can be recovered.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Thus, symplectic conditions and indirect conditions can be said to be equivalent in the context of using generating functions.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] with various forms of generating function, the relation between K and H goes as ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial G}{\partial t}}=K-\lambda H}$ instead, which also applies for ${\textstyle \lambda =1}$ case.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] All results presented below can also be obtained by replacing ${\textstyle q\rightarrow {\sqrt {\lambda }}q}$ , ${\textstyle p\rightarrow {\sqrt {\lambda }}p}$ and ${\textstyle H\rightarrow {\lambda }H}$ from known solutions, since it retains the form of Hamilton's equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] The second part of each equation cancel.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Hence the condition for extended canonical transformation instead becomes: ${\textstyle MJM^{T}=\lambda J}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p01] Hence, the Poisson bracket scales by the inverse of ${\textstyle \lambda }$ whereas the Lagrange bracket scales by a factor of ${\textstyle \lambda }$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] For infinitesimal values of $\alpha$ , the corresponding transformations are called as *infinitesimal canonical transformations* which are also known as differential canonical transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Since for $\alpha =0$ , $G_{2}=qP$ has the resulting canonical transformation, $Q=q$ and $P=p$ , this type of generating function can be used for infinitesimal canonical transformation by restricting $\alpha$ to an infinitesimal value.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Infinitesimal canonical transformations can also be derived using the matrix form of the symplectic condition.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] The function $G(q,p,t)$ is very significant in infinitesimal canonical transformations and is referred to as the generator of infinitesimal canonical transformation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] In the active view of transformations, the coordinate system is changed without the physical system changing, whereas in the passive view of transformation, the coordinate system is retained and the physical system is said to undergo transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] or as $\delta \eta =\alpha J\nabla _{\eta }G$ in matrix form.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] where ${\textstyle (q=q_{0}',p=p_{0}')}$ are mapped to the point, ${\textstyle (Q=q_{0},P=p_{0})}$ by the infinitesimal canonical transformation, and similar change of variables for $G(q,P,t)$ to $G(q,p,t)$ is considered up-to first order of $\alpha$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, if the Hamiltonian is invariant for infinitesimal canonical transformations, its generator is a constant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Consider the transformation where the change of coordinates also depends on the generalized velocities.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] and the new Lagrangian is said to be dynamically equivalent to the old Lagrangian as it ensures the resultant equations of motion being the same.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, the term $p\phi -F$ generates the canonical dynamical symmetry transformation if either the Euler Lagrange relation gives zero, or if ${\frac {\partial \phi _{s}}{\partial {\dot {q}}^{r}}}=0\,\forall s,r$ which is a infinitesimal point transformation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Note that in the point transformation condition, the quantity generates the transformation regardless of if the Euler Lagrange equations are satisfied and since they do not depend on the dynamics of the problem are said to be a purely kinematic relation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Similar results are obtained in classical field theory, for example, in a Lorentz invariant Lagrangian density where corresponding conserved charges, momentum density $P^{\mu }$ generates translation of fields and $M^{\mu \nu }$ of Lorentz invariance generates Lorentz transformation of fields.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence $\left(\phi {\frac {\partial }{\partial {\dot {q}}}}L-F\right)=p\phi -F$ is a constant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, the derived Noether invariant also generates the same symmetry transformation as shown previously.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Thus the continuous application of such a transformation maps the coordinates $\eta (\tau )$ to $\eta (\tau +t)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence if the Hamiltonian is time translation invariant, i.e. does not have explicit time dependence, its value is conserved for the motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, the canonical momentum generates a shift in the corresponding generalized coordinate and if the Hamiltonian is invariant of translation, the momentum is a constant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] These transformations correspond to rotation about the z axis by angle $\delta \phi$ in its first order approximation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, repeated application of the infinitesimal canonical transformation generates a rotation of system of particles about the z axis.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] If the Hamiltonian is invariant under rotation about the z axis, the generator, the component of angular momentum along the axis of rotation, is an invariant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] for all $\eta$ given that the generator has no explicit dependence on $\alpha$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence one parameter subgroups of canonical transformations are extension of infinitesimal canonical transformations to finite values of $\alpha$ by using the same functional form of its generator independent of parameter $\alpha$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] As a consequence of the generator having no explicit dependence on $\alpha$ , the generator is also implicitly independent of $\alpha$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] where the linear differential operator is defined as ${\tilde {G}}:=(\nabla _{\eta }G)^{T}J\nabla _{\eta }$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] It is also possible that functions transform without needing to preserve its values on the same physical states in phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] which is similar to previous relation but also accounts for any explicit time dependence of the generator.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Hence, if the Hamiltonian is invariant in passive view for infinitesimal canonical transformations, its generator is a constant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Motion itself (or, equivalently, a shift in the time origin) is a canonical transformation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] In mathematical terms, canonical coordinates are any coordinates on the phase space (cotangent bundle) of the system that allow the canonical one-form to be written as $\sum _{i}p_{i}\,dq^{i}$ up to a total differential (exact form).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] The change of variable between one set of canonical coordinates and another is a **canonical transformation**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] The index of the generalized coordinates **q** is written here as a *superscript* ( $q^{i}$ ), not as a *subscript* as done above ( $q_{i}$ ).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] The superscript conveys the contravariant transformation properties of the generalized coordinates, and does *not* mean that the coordinate is being raised to a power.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] Further details may be found at the symplectomorphism article.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] The first major application of the canonical transformation was in 1846, by Charles Delaunay, in the study of the Earth-Moon-Sun system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/canonical-transformation-p02] This work resulted in the publication of a pair of large volumes as *Mémoires* by the French Academy of Sciences, in 1860 and 1867.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] In physics, the **Hamilton–Jacobi equation**, named after William Rowan Hamilton and Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi, is an alternative formulation of classical mechanics, equivalent to other formulations such as Newton's laws of motion, Lagrangian mechanics and Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The Hamilton–Jacobi equation is a formulation of mechanics in which the motion of a particle can be represented as a wave.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] In this sense, it fulfilled a long-held goal of theoretical physics (dating at least to Johann Bernoulli in the eighteenth century) of finding an analogy between the propagation of light and the motion of a particle.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The wave equation followed by mechanical systems is similar to, but not identical with, the Schrödinger equation, as described below; for this reason, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation is considered the "closest approach" of classical mechanics to quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The qualitative form of this connection is called Hamilton's optico-mechanical analogy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] In mathematics, the Hamilton–Jacobi equation is a necessary condition describing extremal geometry in generalizations of problems from the calculus of variations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] It can be understood as a special case of the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equation from dynamic programming.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] for a system of particles at coordinates ⁠ $\mathbf {q}$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The function H is the system's Hamiltonian giving the system's energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The solution of this equation is the *action*, ⁠ S ⁠, called *Hamilton's principal function*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] This property of the Hamilton–Jacobi equation connects classical mechanics to quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] A dot over a variable or list signifies the time derivative (see Newton's notation).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Let a time instant $t_{0}$ and a point $\mathbf {q} _{0}\in M$ in the configuration space be fixed.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The momenta are defined as the quantities ${\textstyle p_{i}(\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {\dot {q}} ,t)=\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial {\dot {q}}^{i}.}$ This section shows that the dependency of $p_{i}$ on $\mathbf {\dot {q}}$ disappears, once the HPF is known.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Indeed, let a time instant $t_{0}$ and a point $\mathbf {q} _{0}$ in the configuration space be fixed.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For every time instant t and a point $\mathbf {q} ,$ let $\gamma =\gamma (\tau ;t,t_{0},\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {q} _{0})$ be the (unique) extremal from the definition of the Hamilton's principal function ⁠ S ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] While the proof below assumes the configuration space to be an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ the underlying technique applies equally to arbitrary spaces.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] In the context of this proof, the calligraphic letter ${\mathcal {S}}$ denotes the action functional, and the italic S the Hamilton's principal function.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Since $\xi$ now satisfies the Euler–Lagrange equations, the integral term vanishes.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Here, we took into account that $\mathbf {q} =\gamma (t;\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {q} _{0},t,t_{0})$ and dropped $t_{0}$ for compactness.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] As a solution to the Hamilton–Jacobi equation, the principal function contains $N+1$ undetermined constants, the first N of them denoted as $\alpha _{1},\,\alpha _{2},\dots ,\alpha _{N}$ , and the last one coming from the integration of ${\frac {\partial S}{\partial t}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The relationship between $\mathbf {p}$ and $\mathbf {q}$ then describes the orbit in phase space in terms of these constants of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Furthermore, the quantities $\beta _{k}={\frac {\partial S}{\partial \alpha _{k}}},\quad k=1,2,\ldots ,N$ are also constants of motion, and these equations can be inverted to find $\mathbf {q}$ as a function of all the $\alpha$ and $\beta$ constants and time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The Hamilton–Jacobi equation is a *single*, first-order partial differential equation for the function of the N generalized coordinates $q_{1},\,q_{2},\dots ,q_{N}$ and the time t .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The generalized momenta do not appear, except as derivatives of S , the classical action.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For comparison, in the equivalent Euler–Lagrange equations of motion of Lagrangian mechanics, the conjugate momenta also do not appear; however, those equations are a *system* of N , generally second-order equations for the time evolution of the generalized coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Similarly, Hamilton's equations of motion are another *system* of 2*N* first-order equations for the time evolution of the generalized coordinates and their conjugate momenta $p_{1},\,p_{2},\dots ,p_{N}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For example, the Hamilton–Jacobi equations can be used to determine the geodesics on a Riemannian manifold, an important variational problem in Riemannian geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] However as a computational tool, the partial differential equations are notoriously complicated to solve except when is it possible to separate the independent variables; in this case the HJE become computationally useful.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] To derive the HJE, a generating function $G_{2}(\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {P} ,t)$ is chosen in such a way that, it will make the new Hamiltonian $K=0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Hence, all its derivatives are also zero, and the transformed Hamilton's equations become trivial ${\dot {\mathbf {P} }}={\dot {\mathbf {Q} }}=0$ so the new generalized coordinates and momenta are *constants* of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Ideally, these N equations can be inverted to find the original generalized coordinates $\mathbf {q}$ as a function of the constants ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }},\,{\boldsymbol {\beta }},$ and t , thus solving the original problem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] When the problem allows additive separation of variables, the HJE leads directly to constants of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For example, the time *t* can be separated if the Hamiltonian does not depend on time explicitly.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] In such a case, the problem devolves to N ordinary differential equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The separability of *S* depends both on the Hamiltonian and on the choice of generalized coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For illustration, several examples in orthogonal coordinates are worked in the next sections.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The last term has few physical applications.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] This reduces the HJE to the ordinary differential equations whose integration completes the solution for S .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The HJE establishes a duality between trajectories and wavefronts.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] For example, in geometrical optics, light can be considered either as "rays" or waves.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The wave front can be defined as the surface ${\textstyle {\mathcal {C}}_{t}}$ that the light emitted at time ${\textstyle t=0}$ has reached at time ${\textstyle t}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Light rays and wave fronts are dual: if one is known, the other can be deduced.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] More precisely, geometrical optics is a variational problem where the "action" is the travel time ${\textstyle T}$ along a path, $T={\frac {1}{c}}\int _{A}^{B}n\,ds$ where ${\textstyle n}$ is the medium's index of refraction and ${\textstyle ds}$ is an infinitesimal arc length.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] From the above formulation, one can compute the ray paths using the Euler–Lagrange formulation; alternatively, one can compute the wave fronts by solving the Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The above duality is very general and applies to *all* systems that derive from a variational principle: either compute the trajectories using Euler–Lagrange equations or the wave fronts by using Hamilton–Jacobi equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The wave front at time ${\textstyle t}$ , for a system initially at ${\textstyle \mathbf {q} _{0}}$ at time ${\textstyle t_{0}}$ , is defined as the collection of points ${\textstyle \mathbf {q} }$ such that ${\textstyle S(\mathbf {q} ,t)={\text{const}}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The trajectories are then recovered from the knowledge of ${\textstyle {\dot {\mathbf {q} }}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The isosurfaces of the function $S(\mathbf {q} ,t)$ can be determined at any time *t*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The motion of an S -isosurface as a function of time is defined by the motions of the particles beginning at the points $\mathbf {q}$ on the isosurface.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The motion of such an isosurface can be thought of as a *wave* moving through $\mathbf {q}$ -space, although it does not obey the wave equation exactly.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Starting with the Schrödinger equation and our ansatz for $\psi$ , it can be deduced that ${\frac {1}{2m}}\left(\nabla S\right)^{2}+U+{\frac {\partial S}{\partial t}}={\frac {i\hbar }{2m}}\nabla ^{2}S.$ This is the Schrödinger equation in nonlinear Riccati form.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The following table summarizes the similarities between optics and quantum mechancis.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The Hamilton-Jacobi equation is to quantum mechanics what the eikonal equation is to the wave equation of optics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] Both the eikonal equation and the Hamilton-Jacobi equation are slowly varying approximations (WKB approximations) of the corresponding more fundamental wave equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] where $\xi _{1}=\xi /c$ , implying the particle moving along a circular trajectory with a permanent radius $ecE_{0}/\gamma \omega ^{2}$ and an invariable value of momentum $eE_{0}/\omega ^{2}$ directed along a magnetic field vector.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] implying the particle figure-8 trajectory with its axis oriented along the electric field E vector.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-jacobi-equation] The particle motion occurs along the figure-8 trajectory in $yz$ plane set perpendicular to the solenoid axis with arbitrary azimuth angle $\varphi$ due to axial symmetry of the solenoidal magnetic field.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In physics, **Hamiltonian mechanics** is a reformulation of Lagrangian mechanics that emerged in 1833.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Introduced by Sir William Rowan Hamilton, Hamiltonian mechanics replaces (generalized) velocities ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ used in Lagrangian mechanics with (generalized) *momenta*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Both theories provide interpretations of classical mechanics and describe the same physical phenomena.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hamiltonian mechanics has a close relationship with geometry (notably, symplectic geometry and Poisson structures) and serves as a link between classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] (Also *generalized momenta*, *conjugate momenta*, and *canonical momenta*).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Legendre transform of ${\mathcal {L}}$ turns $E_{\mathcal {L}}$ into a function ${\mathcal {H}}({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}},t)$ known as the **Hamiltonian**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The ( $2n$ -dimensional) pair $({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}})$ is called *phase space coordinates*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] By rearranging the equation ${\boldsymbol {p}}=\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial {\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ , we can write ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ in terms of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ as ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {p}})$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] So **1** becomes an equation in two variables: ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A path ${\boldsymbol {q}}\in {\mathcal {P}}(a,b,{\boldsymbol {x}}_{a},{\boldsymbol {x}}_{b})$ is a stationary point of ${\mathcal {S}}$ (and hence is an equation of motion) if and only if the path $({\boldsymbol {p}}(t),{\boldsymbol {q}}(t))$ in phase space coordinates obeys the Hamilton equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A simple interpretation of Hamiltonian mechanics comes from its application on a one-dimensional system consisting of one nonrelativistic particle of mass m.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The value $H(p,q)$ of the Hamiltonian is the total energy of the system, in this case the sum of kinetic and potential energy, traditionally denoted T and V, respectively.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Here p is the momentum mv and q is the space coordinate.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Then ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V,\qquad T={\frac {p^{2}}{2m}},\qquad V=V(q)$ T is a function of p alone, while V is a function of q alone (i.e., T and V are scleronomic).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In this example, the time derivative of q is the velocity, and so the first Hamilton equation means that the particle's velocity equals the derivative of its kinetic energy with respect to its momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The time derivative of the momentum p equals the *Newtonian force*, and so the second Hamilton equation means that the force equals the negative gradient of potential energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A spherical pendulum consists of a mass *m* moving without friction on the surface of a sphere.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The only forces acting on the mass are the reaction from the sphere and gravity.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Spherical coordinates are used to describe the position of the mass in terms of (*r*, *θ*, *φ*), where *r* is fixed, *r* = *ℓ*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] That is a consequence of the rotational symmetry of the system around the vertical axis.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Being absent from the Hamiltonian, azimuth $\varphi$ is a cyclic coordinate, which implies conservation of its conjugate momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hamilton's equations can be derived by a calculation with the Lagrangian ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, generalized positions qi, and generalized velocities ⋅*q**i*, where ⁠ $i=1,\ldots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Here we work off-shell, meaning ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ t ⁠ are independent coordinates in phase space, not constrained to follow any equations of motion (in particular, ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ is not a derivative of ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In the case of time-independent ${\mathcal {H}}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, i.e. ⁠ $\partial {\mathcal {H}}/\partial t=-\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial t=0$ ⁠, Hamilton's equations consist of 2*n* first-order differential equations, while Lagrange's equations consist of n second-order equations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hamilton's equations usually do not reduce the difficulty of finding explicit solutions, but important theoretical results can be derived from them, because coordinates and momenta are independent variables with nearly symmetric roles.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This effectively reduces the problem from n coordinates to (*n* − 1) coordinates: this is the basis of symplectic reduction in geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In the Lagrangian framework, the conservation of momentum also follows immediately, however all the generalized velocities ${\dot {q}}_{i}$ still occur in the Lagrangian, and a system of equations in n coordinates still has to be solved.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Lagrangian and Hamiltonian approaches provide the groundwork for deeper results in classical mechanics, and suggest analogous formulations in quantum mechanics: the path integral formulation and the Schrödinger equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] where T is the kinetic energy and V is the potential energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Using this relation can be simpler than first calculating the Lagrangian, and then deriving the Hamiltonian from the Lagrangian.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] However, the relation is not true for all systems.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] where t is time, n is the number of degrees of freedom of the system, and each $c_{ij}({\boldsymbol {q}})$ is an arbitrary scalar function of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In words, this means that the relation ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ holds true if T does not contain time as an explicit variable (it is scleronomic), V does not contain generalised velocity as an explicit variable, and each term of T is quadratic in generalised velocity.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Preliminary to this proof, it is important to address an ambiguity in the related mathematical notation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In this case, the right hand side always evaluates to 0.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] To perform a change of variables inside of a partial derivative, the multivariable chain rule should be used.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hence, to avoid ambiguity, the function arguments of any term inside of a partial derivative should be stated.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Additionally, this proof uses the notation $f(a,b,c)=f(a,b)$ to imply that ${\frac {\partial f(a,b,c)}{\partial c}}=0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] where each $c_{ij}({\boldsymbol {q}})$ is an arbitrary scalar function of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This simplification is a result of Euler's homogeneous function theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] For a system of point masses, the requirement for T to be quadratic in generalised velocity is always satisfied for the case where $T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}},t)=T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}})$ , which is a requirement for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ anyway.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Consider the kinetic energy for a system of N point masses.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] If the conditions for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ are satisfied, then conservation of the Hamiltonian implies conservation of energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This requires the additional condition that V does not contain time as an explicit variable.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Regarding extensions to the Euler-Lagrange formulation which use dissipation functions (See *Lagrangian mechanics § Extensions to include non-conservative forces*), e.g. the Rayleigh dissipation function, energy is not conserved when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] It is possible to explain the link between this and the former requirements by relating the extended and conventional Euler-Lagrange equations: grouping the extended terms into the potential function produces a velocity dependent potential.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hence, the requirements are not satisfied when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A sufficient illustration of Hamiltonian mechanics is given by the Hamiltonian of a charged particle in an electromagnetic field.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This Lagrangian, combined with Euler–Lagrange equation, produces the Lorentz force law $m{\ddot {\mathbf {x} }}=q\mathbf {E} +q{\dot {\mathbf {x} }}\times \mathbf {B} \,,$ and is called minimal coupling.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This equation is used frequently in quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Under gauge transformation: $\mathbf {A} \rightarrow \mathbf {A} +\nabla f\,,\quad \varphi \rightarrow \varphi -{\dot {f}}\,,$ where *f*(**r**, *t*) is any scalar function of space and time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In quantum mechanics, the wave function will also undergo a local U(1) group transformation during the Gauge Transformation, which implies that all physical results must be invariant under local U(1) transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] As a closed nondegenerate symplectic 2-form *ω*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Due to the bilinearity and non-degeneracy of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and the fact that ⁠ $\dim T_{x}M=\dim T_{x}^{*}M$ ⁠, the mapping $\xi \to \omega _{\xi }$ is indeed a linear isomorphism.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This isomorphism is *natural* in that it does not change with change of coordinates on $M.$ Repeating over all ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠, we end up with an isomorphism $J^{-1}:{\text{Vect}}(M)\to \Omega ^{1}(M)$ between the infinite-dimensional space of smooth vector fields and that of smooth 1-forms.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] (In algebraic terms, one would say that the $C^{\infty }(M,\mathbb {R} )$ -modules ${\text{Vect}}(M)$ and $\Omega ^{1}(M)$ are isomorphic).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The respective differential equation on M ${\dot {x}}=J(dH)(x)$ is called *Hamilton's equation*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Here $x=x(t)$ and $J(dH)(x)\in T_{x}M$ is the (time-dependent) value of the vector field $J(dH)$ at ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A Hamiltonian system may be understood as a fiber bundle E over time R, with the fiber Et being the position space at time *t* ∈ *R*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The correspondence between Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics is achieved with the tautological one-form.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Any smooth real-valued function H on a symplectic manifold can be used to define a Hamiltonian system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The function H is known as "the Hamiltonian" or "the energy function." The symplectic manifold is then called the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Hamiltonian induces a special vector field on the symplectic manifold, known as the Hamiltonian vector field.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Hamiltonian vector field induces a Hamiltonian flow on the manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This is a one-parameter family of transformations of the manifold (the parameter of the curves is commonly called "the time"); in other words, an isotopy of symplectomorphisms, starting with the identity.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] By Liouville's theorem, each symplectomorphism preserves the volume form on the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The collection of symplectomorphisms induced by the Hamiltonian flow is commonly called "the Hamiltonian mechanics" of the Hamiltonian system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The symplectic structure induces a Poisson bracket.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Poisson bracket gives the space of functions on the manifold the structure of a Lie algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] If F and G are smooth functions on M then the smooth function *ω*(*J*(*dF*), *J*(*dG*)) is properly defined; it is called a *Poisson bracket* of functions F and G and is denoted {*F*, *G*}.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] 5. non-degeneracy: if the point x on M is not critical for F then a smooth function G exists such that ⁠ $\{F,G\}(x)\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Every smooth function G over the symplectic manifold generates a one-parameter family of symplectomorphisms and if {*G*, *H*} = 0, then G is conserved and the symplectomorphisms are symmetry transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A Hamiltonian may have multiple conserved quantities *G**i*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] If the symplectic manifold has dimension 2*n* and there are n functionally independent conserved quantities Gi which are in involution (i.e., {*G**i*, *G**j*} = 0), then the Hamiltonian is Liouville integrable.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Liouville–Arnold theorem says that, locally, any Liouville integrable Hamiltonian can be transformed via a symplectomorphism into a new Hamiltonian with the conserved quantities Gi as coordinates; the new coordinates are called *action–angle coordinates*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The transformed Hamiltonian depends only on the *G**i*, and hence the equations of motion have the simple form ${\dot {G}}_{i}=0\quad ,\quad {\dot {\varphi }}_{i}=F_{i}(G)$ for some function F.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] There is an entire field focusing on small deviations from integrable systems governed by the KAM theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The integrability of Hamiltonian vector fields is an open question.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In general, Hamiltonian systems are chaotic; concepts of measure, completeness, integrability and stability are poorly defined.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This Hamiltonian consists entirely of the kinetic term.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] If one considers a Riemannian manifold or a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, the Riemannian metric induces a linear isomorphism between the tangent and cotangent bundles.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Using this isomorphism, one can define a cometric.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] (In coordinates, the matrix defining the cometric is the inverse of the matrix defining the metric.) The solutions to the Hamilton–Jacobi equations for this Hamiltonian are then the same as the geodesics on the manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In particular, the Hamiltonian flow in this case is the same thing as the geodesic flow.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The existence of such solutions, and the completeness of the set of solutions, are discussed in detail in the article on geodesics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] See also *Geodesics as Hamiltonian flows*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] When the cometric is degenerate, then it is not invertible.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In this case, one does not have a Riemannian manifold, as one does not have a metric.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] In the case where the cometric is degenerate at every point q of the configuration space manifold Q, so that the rank of the cometric is less than the dimension of the manifold Q, one has a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The Hamiltonian in this case is known as a **sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Every such Hamiltonian uniquely determines the cometric, and vice versa.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This implies that every sub-Riemannian manifold is uniquely determined by its sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian, and that the converse is true: every sub-Riemannian manifold has a unique sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The existence of sub-Riemannian geodesics is given by the Chow–Rashevskii theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] The continuous, real-valued Heisenberg group provides a simple example of a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hamiltonian systems can be generalized in various ways.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Instead of simply looking at the algebra of smooth functions over a symplectic manifold, Hamiltonian mechanics can be formulated on general commutative unital real Poisson algebras.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A state is a continuous linear functional on the Poisson algebra (equipped with some suitable topology) such that for any element A of the algebra, *A*2 maps to a nonnegative real number.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] A further generalization is given by Nambu dynamics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Hamilton's equations above work well for classical mechanics, but not for quantum mechanics, since the differential equations discussed assume that one can specify the exact position and momentum of the particle simultaneously at any point in time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] However, the equations can be further generalized to then be extended to apply to quantum mechanics as well as to classical mechanics, through the deformation of the Poisson algebra over p and q to the algebra of Moyal brackets.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Specifically, the more general form of the Hamilton's equation reads ${\frac {\mathrm {d} f}{\mathrm {d} t}}=\left\{f,{\mathcal {H}}\right\}+{\frac {\partial f}{\partial t}},$ where f is some function of p and q, and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] To find out the rules for evaluating a Poisson bracket without resorting to differential equations, see *Lie algebra*; a Poisson bracket is the name for the Lie bracket in a Poisson algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] These Poisson brackets can then be extended to Moyal brackets comporting to an inequivalent Lie algebra, as proven by Hilbrand J.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] Groenewold, and thereby describe quantum mechanical diffusion in phase space (See *Phase space formulation* and *Wigner–Weyl transform*).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/hamilton-s-equations] This more algebraic approach not only permits ultimately extending probability distributions in phase space to Wigner quasi-probability distributions, but, at the mere Poisson bracket classical setting, also provides more power in helping analyze the relevant conserved quantities in a system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In physics, **Liouville's theorem**, named after the French mathematician Joseph Liouville, is a key theorem in classical statistical and Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] It asserts that *the phase-space distribution function is constant along the trajectories of the system*—that is that the density of system points in the vicinity of a given system point traveling through phase-space is constant with time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This time-independent density is in statistical mechanics known as the classical a priori probability.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Liouville's theorem applies to conservative systems, that is, systems in which the effects of friction are absent or can be ignored.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The general mathematical formulation for such systems is the measure-preserving dynamical system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Liouville's theorem applies when there are degrees of freedom that can be interpreted as positions and momenta; not all measure-preserving dynamical systems have these, but Hamiltonian systems do.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The general setting for conjugate position and momentum coordinates is available in the mathematical setting of symplectic geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Liouville's theorem ignores the possibility of chemical reactions, where the total number of particles may change over time, or where energy may be transferred to internal degrees of freedom.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The non-squeezing theorem, which applies to all symplectic maps (the Hamiltonian is a symplectic map) implies further restrictions on phase-space flows beyond volume/density/measure conservation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] There are extensions of Liouville's theorem to cover these various generalized settings, including stochastic systems.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The Liouville equation describes the time evolution of the *phase space distribution function*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Josiah Willard Gibbs was the first to recognize this as the fundamental equation of statistical mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] It is referred to as the Liouville equation because its derivation for non-canonical systems utilises an identity first derived by Liouville in 1838.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Consider a Hamiltonian dynamical system with canonical coordinates $q_{i}$ and conjugate momenta $p_{i}$ , where $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Time derivatives are denoted by dots, and are evaluated according to Hamilton's equations for the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This equation demonstrates the conservation of density in phase space (which was Gibbs's name for the theorem).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The distribution function is constant along any trajectory in phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] A proof of Liouville's theorem uses the *n*-dimensional divergence theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The above equation means that change of the total probability within a small volume in phase space is equal to the net flux of probability density into or out of the volume.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] where H is the Hamiltonian, and we have used the relationships ${\dot {q}}_{i}=\partial H/\partial p_{i}$ and ${\dot {p}}_{i}=-\partial H/\partial {q_{i}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The derivation of the Liouville equation can be viewed as the motion through phase space as a 'fluid flow' of system points.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The theorem that the convective derivative of the density, $d\rho /dt$ , is zero follows from the equation of continuity by noting that the 'velocity field' $({\dot {p}},{\dot {q}})$ in phase space has zero divergence (which follows from Hamilton's relations).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In ergodic theory and dynamical systems, motivated by the physical considerations given so far, there is a corresponding result also referred to as Liouville's theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In Hamiltonian mechanics, the phase space is a smooth manifold that comes naturally equipped with a smooth measure (locally, this measure is the 6*n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The theorem says this smooth measure is invariant under the Hamiltonian flow.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] More generally, one can describe the necessary and sufficient condition under which a smooth measure is invariant under a flow.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The Hamiltonian case then becomes a corollary.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] We can also formulate Liouville's Theorem in terms of symplectic geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] $\omega =dp_{\mu }\wedge dq^{\mu }.$ The volume form of our manifold is the top exterior power of the symplectic 2-form, and is just another representation of the measure on the phase space described above.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] where we utilized Hamilton's equations of motion and the definition of the chain rule.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In this formalism, Liouville's Theorem states that the Lie derivative of the volume form is zero along the flow generated by $X_{H}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In fact, the symplectic structure $\omega$ itself is preserved, not only its top exterior power.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The analog of Liouville equation in quantum mechanics describes the time evolution of a mixed state.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Canonical quantization yields a quantum-mechanical version of this theorem, the von Neumann equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This procedure, often used to devise quantum analogues of classical systems, involves describing a classical system using Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Classical variables are then re-interpreted as quantum operators, while Poisson brackets are replaced by commutators.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In this case, the resulting equation is ${\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}={\frac {1}{i\hbar }}[H,\rho ],$ where ρ is the density matrix.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Note the sign difference, which follows from the assumption that the operator is stationary and the state is time-dependent.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] In the phase-space formulation of quantum mechanics, substituting the Moyal brackets for Poisson brackets in the phase-space analog of the von Neumann equation results in compressibility of the probability fluid, and thus violations of Liouville's theorem incompressibility.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This, then, leads to concomitant difficulties in defining meaningful quantum trajectories.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Consider an N -particle system in three dimensions, and focus on only the evolution of $\mathrm {d} {\mathcal {N}}$ particles.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] We want ${\frac {\mathrm {d} {\mathcal {N}}}{\mathrm {d} \Gamma }}$ to remain the same throughout time, so that $\rho (\Gamma ,t)$ is constant along the trajectories of the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] To find the new infinitesimal phase-space volume $\mathrm {d} \Gamma '$ , we need the product of the above quantities.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] So far, we have yet to make any specifications about our system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Let us now specialize to the case of N 3 -dimensional isotropic harmonic oscillators.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] That is, each particle in our ensemble can be treated as a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] demonstrating that Liouville's theorem holds for this system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The question remains of how the phase-space volume actually evolves in time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Above we have shown that the total volume is conserved, but said nothing about what it looks like.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] For a single particle we can see that its trajectory in phase space is given by the ellipse of constant H .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] where $Q_{i}$ and $P_{i}$ denote the initial position and momentum of the i -th particle.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] For a system of multiple particles, each one will have a phase-space trajectory that traces out an ellipse corresponding to the particle's energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] The frequency at which the ellipse is traced is given by the $\omega$ in the Hamiltonian, independent of any differences in energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] As a result, a region of phase space will simply rotate about the point $(\mathbf {q} ,\mathbf {p} )=(0,0)$ with frequency dependent on $\omega$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This can be seen in the animation above.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] To see an example where Liouville's theorem does *not* apply, we can modify the equations of motion for the simple harmonic oscillator to account for the effects of friction or damping.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Consider again the system of N particles each in a 3 -dimensional isotropic harmonic potential, the Hamiltonian for which is given in the previous example.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] This time, we add the condition that each particle experiences a frictional force $-\gamma p_{i}$ , where $\gamma$ is a positive constant dictating the amount of friction.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Unlike the equations of motion for the simple harmonic oscillator, these modified equations do not take the form of Hamilton's equations, and therefore we do not expect Liouville's theorem to hold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Instead, as depicted in the animation in this section, a generic phase space volume will shrink as it evolves under these equations of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] We have found that the infinitesimal phase-space volume is no longer constant, and thus the phase-space density is not conserved.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] As can be seen from the equation as time increases, we expect our phase-space volume to decrease to zero as friction affects the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] As for how the phase-space volume evolves in time, we will still have the constant rotation as in the undamped case.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] However, the damping will introduce a steady decrease in the radii of each ellipse.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] Again we can solve for the trajectories explicitly using Hamilton's equations, taking care to use the modified ones above.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] where the values $Q_{i}$ and $P_{i}$ denote the initial position and momentum of the i -th particle.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/liouville-s-theorem-hamiltonian] As the system evolves the total phase-space volume will spiral in to the origin.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The **phase space** of a physical system is the set of all possible physical states of the system when described by a given parameterization.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Each possible state corresponds uniquely to a point in the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] For mechanical systems, the phase space usually consists of all possible values of the position and momentum parameters.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] It is the direct product of direct space and reciprocal space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The concept of phase space was developed in the late 19th century by Ludwig Boltzmann, Henri Poincaré, and Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In a phase space, every degree of freedom or parameter of the system is represented as an axis of a multidimensional space; a one-dimensional system is called a phase line, while a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] For every possible state of the system or allowed combination of values of the system's parameters, a point is included in the multidimensional space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The system's evolving state over time traces a path (a **phase-space trajectory** for the system) through the high-dimensional space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The phase-space trajectory represents the set of states compatible with starting from one particular initial condition, located in the full phase space that represents the set of states compatible with starting from *any* initial condition.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] As a whole, the phase diagram represents all that the system can be, and its shape can easily elucidate qualities of the system that might not be obvious otherwise.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] A phase space may contain a great number of dimensions.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In classical mechanics, any choice of generalized coordinates *q**i* for the position (i.e. coordinates on configuration space) defines conjugate generalized momenta *p**i*, which together define co-ordinates on phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The motion of an ensemble of systems in this space is studied by classical statistical mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The local density of points in such systems obeys Liouville's theorem, and so can be taken as constant.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Within the context of a model system in classical mechanics, the phase-space coordinates of the system at any given time are composed of all of the system's dynamic variables.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Because of this, it is possible to calculate the state of the system at any given time in the future or the past, through integration of Hamilton's or Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] For simple systems, there may be as few as one or two degrees of freedom.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] One degree of freedom occurs when one has an autonomous ordinary differential equation in a single variable, $dy/dt=f(y),$ with the resulting one-dimensional system being called a phase line, and the qualitative behaviour of the system being immediately visible from the phase line.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The simplest non-trivial examples are the exponential growth model/decay (one unstable/stable equilibrium) and the logistic growth model (two equilibria, one stable, one unstable).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The phase space of a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane, which occurs in classical mechanics for a single particle moving in one dimension, and where the two variables are position and velocity.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In this case, a sketch of the phase portrait may give qualitative information about the dynamics of the system, such as the limit cycle of the Van der Pol oscillator shown in the diagram.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Here the horizontal axis gives the position, and vertical axis the velocity.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] As the system evolves, its state follows one of the lines (trajectories) on the phase diagram.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] A plot of position and momentum variables as a function of time is sometimes called a **phase plot** or a **phase diagram**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] However the latter expression, "phase diagram", is more usually reserved in the physical sciences for a diagram showing the various regions of stability of the thermodynamic phases of a chemical system, which consists of pressure, temperature, and composition.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In mathematics, a phase portrait is a geometric representation of the orbits of a dynamical system in the phase plane.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Each set of initial conditions is represented by a different point or curve.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Phase portraits are an invaluable tool in studying dynamical systems.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] They consist of a plot of typical trajectories in the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] This reveals information such as whether an attractor, a repellor or limit cycle is present for the chosen parameter value.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The concept of topological equivalence is important in classifying the behaviour of systems by specifying when two different phase portraits represent the same qualitative dynamic behavior.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] An attractor is a stable point which is also called a "sink".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The repeller is considered as an unstable point, which is also known as a "source".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] A phase portrait graph of a dynamical system depicts the system's trajectories (with arrows) and stable steady states (with dots) and unstable steady states (with circles) in a phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In classical statistical mechanics (continuous energies) the concept of phase space provides a classical analog to the partition function (sum over states) known as the phase integral.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Instead of summing the Boltzmann factor over discretely spaced energy states (defined by appropriate integer quantum numbers for each degree of freedom), one may integrate over continuous phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Such integration essentially consists of two parts: integration of the momentum component of all degrees of freedom (momentum space) and integration of the position component of all degrees of freedom (configuration space).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Once the phase integral is known, it may be related to the classical partition function by multiplication of a normalization constant representing the number of quantum energy states per unit phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] This normalization constant is simply the inverse of the Planck constant raised to a power equal to the number of degrees of freedom for the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In quantum mechanics, the coordinates *p* and *q* of phase space normally become Hermitian operators in a Hilbert space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] But they may alternatively retain their classical interpretation, provided functions of them compose in novel algebraic ways (through Groenewold's 1946 star product).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] This is consistent with the uncertainty principle of quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Every quantum mechanical observable corresponds to a unique function or distribution on phase space, and conversely, as specified by Hermann Weyl (1927) and supplemented by John von Neumann (1931); Eugene Wigner (1932); and, in a grand synthesis, by H.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Moyal (1949), these completed the foundations of the **phase-space formulation of quantum mechanics**, a complete and logically autonomous reformulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Expectation values in phase-space quantization are obtained isomorphically to tracing operator observables with the density matrix in Hilbert space: they are obtained by phase-space integrals of observables, with the Wigner quasi-probability distribution effectively serving as a measure.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In thermodynamics and statistical mechanics contexts, the term "phase space" has two meanings: for one, it is used in the same sense as in classical mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] If a thermodynamic system consists of *N* particles, then a point in the 6*N*-dimensional phase space describes the dynamic state of every particle in that system, as each particle is associated with 3 position variables and 3 momentum variables.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In this sense, as long as the particles are distinguishable, a point in phase space is said to be a microstate of the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] (For indistinguishable particles a microstate consists of a set of *N*! points, corresponding to all possible exchanges of the *N* particles.) *N* is typically on the order of the Avogadro number, thus describing the system at a microscopic level is often impractical.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] This leads to the use of phase space in a different sense.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] The phase space can also refer to the space that is parameterized by the *macroscopic* states of the system, such as pressure, temperature, etc.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] For instance, one may view the pressure–volume diagram or temperature–entropy diagram as describing part of this phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] A point in this phase space is correspondingly called a macrostate.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] There may easily be more than one microstate with the same macrostate.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] For example, for a fixed temperature, the system could have many dynamic configurations at the microscopic level.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] When used in this sense, a phase is a region of phase space where the system in question is in, for example, the liquid phase, or solid phase, etc.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Since there are many more microstates than macrostates, the phase space in the first sense is usually a manifold of much larger dimensions than in the second sense.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Clearly, many more parameters are required to register every detail of the system down to the molecular or atomic scale than to simply specify, say, the temperature or the pressure of the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] Phase space is extensively used in nonimaging optics, the branch of optics devoted to illumination.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] It is also an important concept in Hamiltonian optics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/phase-space] In medicine and bioengineering, the phase space method is used to visualize multidimensional physiological responses.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] In mathematics and classical mechanics, the **Poisson bracket** is an important binary operation in Hamiltonian mechanics, playing a central role in Hamilton's equations of motion, which govern the time evolution of a Hamiltonian dynamical system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The Poisson bracket also distinguishes a certain class of coordinate transformations, called *canonical transformations*, which map canonical coordinate systems into other canonical coordinate systems.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] A "canonical coordinate system" consists of canonical position and momentum variables (below symbolized by $q_{i}$ and $p_{i}$ , respectively) that satisfy canonical Poisson bracket relations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The set of possible canonical transformations is always very rich.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] For instance, it is often possible to choose the Hamiltonian itself ${\mathcal {H}}={\mathcal {H}}(q,p,t)$ as one of the new canonical momentum coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] In a more general sense, the Poisson bracket is used to define a Poisson algebra, of which the algebra of functions on a Poisson manifold is a special case.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] There are other general examples, as well: it occurs in the theory of Lie algebras, where the tensor algebra of a Lie algebra forms a Poisson algebra; a detailed construction of how this comes about is given in the universal enveloping algebra article.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Quantum deformations of the universal enveloping algebra lead to the notion of quantum groups.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] All of these objects are named in honor of French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] He introduced the Poisson bracket in his 1809 treatise on mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Given two functions f and g that depend on phase space and time, their Poisson bracket $\{f,g\}$ is another function that depends on phase space and time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Also, if a function k is constant over phase space (but may depend on time), then $\{f,\,k\}=0$ for any f .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Hamilton's equations of motion have an equivalent expression in terms of the Poisson bracket.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This may be most directly demonstrated in an explicit coordinate frame.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Suppose that $f(p,q,t)$ is a function on the solution's trajectory-manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] That is, Poisson brackets are preserved in it, so that *any time t* in the solution to Hamilton's equations, $q(t)=\exp(-t\{{\mathcal {H}},\cdot \})q(0),\quad p(t)=\exp(-t\{{\mathcal {H}},\cdot \})p(0),$ can serve as the bracket coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] *Poisson brackets are canonical invariants*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The operator in the convective part of the derivative, $i{\hat {L}}=-\{{\mathcal {H}},\cdot \}$ , is sometimes referred to as the Liouvillian (see Liouville's theorem (Hamiltonian)).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The concept of Poisson brackets can be expanded to that of matrices by defining the Poisson matrix.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] where the ${\textstyle {\mathcal {L}}(\varepsilon )}$ is known as a Lagrange matrix and whose elements correspond to Lagrange brackets.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The last identity can also be stated as the following: $\sum _{k=1}^{2N}\{\eta _{i},\eta _{k}\}[\eta _{k},\eta _{j}]=-\delta _{ij}$ Note that the summation here involves generalized coordinates as well as generalized momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The invariance of Poisson bracket can be expressed as: ${\textstyle \{\varepsilon _{i},\varepsilon _{j}\}_{\eta }=\{\varepsilon _{i},\varepsilon _{j}\}_{\varepsilon }=J_{ij}}$ , which directly leads to the symplectic condition: ${\textstyle MJM^{T}=J}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] An integrable system will have constants of motion in addition to the energy.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Such constants of motion will commute with the Hamiltonian under the Poisson bracket.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Suppose some function $f(p,q)$ is a constant of motion.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This implies that if $p(t),q(t)$ is a trajectory or solution to Hamilton's equations of motion, then along that trajectory: $0={\frac {df}{dt}}$ Where, as above, the intermediate step follows by applying the equations of motion and we assume that f does not explicitly depend on time.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This equation is known as the Liouville equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The content of Liouville's theorem is that the time evolution of a measure given by a distribution function f is given by the above equation.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] If the Poisson bracket of f and g vanishes ( $\{f,g\}=0$ ), then f and g are said to be **in involution**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] In order for a Hamiltonian system to be completely integrable, n independent constants of motion must be in mutual involution, where n is the number of degrees of freedom.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Furthermore, according to **Poisson's Theorem**, if two quantities A and B are explicitly time independent ( $A(p,q),B(p,q)$ ) constants of motion, so is their Poisson bracket $\{A,\,B\}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This follows from the Jacobi identity (see section below).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Let M be a symplectic manifold, that is, a manifold equipped with a symplectic form: a 2-form $\omega$ which is both **closed** (i.e., its exterior derivative $d\omega$ vanishes) and **non-degenerate**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Then if H is a smooth function on M , the Hamiltonian vector field $X_{H}$ can be defined to be $\Omega _{dH}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The **Poisson bracket** $\ \{\cdot ,\,\cdot \}$ on (*M*, *ω*) is a bilinear operation on differentiable functions, defined by $\{f,\,g\}\;=\;\omega (X_{f},\,X_{g})$ ; the Poisson bracket of two functions on *M* is itself a function on *M*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Here *Xgf* denotes the vector field *Xg* applied to the function *f* as a directional derivative, and ${\mathcal {L}}_{X_{g}}f$ denotes the (entirely equivalent) Lie derivative of the function *f*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The $\phi _{x}(t)$ will be symplectomorphisms (canonical transformations) for every *t* as a function of *x* if and only if ${\mathcal {L}}_{\Omega _{\alpha }}\omega \;=\;0$ ; when this is true, Ωα is called a symplectic vector field.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Therefore, Ωα is a symplectic vector field if and only if α is a closed form.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Since $d(df)\;=\;d^{2}f\;=\;0$ , it follows that every Hamiltonian vector field *Xf* is a symplectic vector field, and that the Hamiltonian flow consists of canonical transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This is a fundamental result in Hamiltonian mechanics, governing the time evolution of functions defined on phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] As noted above, when $\{f,{\mathcal {H}}\}=0$ , *f* is a constant of motion of the system.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The Poisson bracket is intimately connected to the Lie bracket of the Hamiltonian vector fields.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Thus, the Poisson bracket on functions corresponds to the Lie bracket of the associated Hamiltonian vector fields.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] We have also shown that the Lie bracket of two symplectic vector fields is a Hamiltonian vector field and hence is also symplectic.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] In the language of abstract algebra, the symplectic vector fields form a subalgebra of the Lie algebra of smooth vector fields on *M*, and the Hamiltonian vector fields form an ideal of this subalgebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The symplectic vector fields are the Lie algebra of the (infinite-dimensional) Lie group of symplectomorphisms of *M*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] It is widely asserted that the Jacobi identity for the Poisson bracket, $\{f,\{g,h\}\}+\{g,\{h,f\}\}+\{h,\{f,g\}\}=0$ follows from the corresponding identity for the Lie bracket of vector fields, but this is true only up to a locally constant function.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] By **(1)**, the operator $\operatorname {ad} _{g}$ is equal to the operator *Xg*.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The proof of the Jacobi identity follows from **(3)** because, up to the factor of -1, the Lie bracket of vector fields is just their commutator as differential operators.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The algebra of smooth functions on M, together with the Poisson bracket forms a Poisson algebra, because it is a Lie algebra under the Poisson bracket, which additionally satisfies Leibniz's rule **(2)**.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] We have shown that every symplectic manifold is a Poisson manifold, that is a manifold with a "curly-bracket" operator on smooth functions such that the smooth functions form a Poisson algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] However, not every Poisson manifold arises in this way, because Poisson manifolds allow for degeneracy which cannot arise in the symplectic case.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Given a smooth vector field X on the configuration space, let $P_{X}$ be its conjugate momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] This important result is worth a short proof.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Write a vector field X at point q in the configuration space as $X_{q}=\sum _{i}X^{i}(q){\frac {\partial }{\partial q^{i}}}$ where ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial }{\partial q^{i}}}}$ is the local coordinate frame.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The conjugate momentum to X has the expression $P_{X}(q,p)=\sum _{i}X^{i}(q)\;p_{i}$ where the $p_{i}$ are the momentum functions conjugate to the coordinates.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The above holds for all $(q,p)$ , giving the desired result.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] Poisson brackets deform to Moyal brackets upon quantization, that is, they generalize to a different Lie algebra, the Moyal algebra, or, equivalently in Hilbert space, quantum commutators.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The Wigner-İnönü group contraction of these (the classical limit, ħ → 0) yields the above Lie algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] To state this more explicitly and precisely, the universal enveloping algebra of the Heisenberg algebra is the Weyl algebra (modulo the relation that the center be the unit).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] The Moyal product is then a special case of the star product on the algebra of symbols.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/poisson-bracket] An explicit definition of the algebra of symbols, and the star product is given in the article on the universal enveloping algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] The term "symplectic", as adopted into mathematics by Hermann Weyl, is a neo-Greek calque of "complex".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Previously, the "symplectic group" had been called the "line complex group".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] "Complex" comes from the Latin *com-plexus*, meaning "braided together" (co- + plexus), while "symplectic" represents the corresponding Greek *sym-plektikos* (συμπλεκτικός "twining or plaiting together, copulative").
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] In both cases, the stems come from the Indo-European root **pleḱ-*, expressing the concept of folding or weaving, and the prefixes suggest "togetherness".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] The name reflects the deep connections between complex and symplectic structures.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] By Darboux's theorem, symplectic manifolds are locally isomorphic to the standard symplectic vector space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Hence they have only global (topological) invariants.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] The term "symplectic topology" is often used interchangeably with "symplectic geometry".
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] A symplectic geometry is defined on a smooth even-dimensional space that is a differentiable manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] On this space is defined a geometric object, the symplectic 2-form, that allows for the measurement of sizes of two-dimensional objects in the space.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] The symplectic form in symplectic geometry plays a role analogous to that of the metric tensor in Riemannian geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Where the metric tensor measures lengths and angles, the symplectic form measures oriented areas.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Symplectic geometry arose from the study of classical mechanics and an example of a symplectic structure is the motion of an object in one dimension.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] To specify the trajectory of the object, one requires both the position *q* and the momentum *p*, which form a point (*p*,*q*) in the Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] The area is important because as conservative dynamical systems evolve in time, this area is invariant.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Higher dimensional symplectic geometries are defined analogously.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Riemannian geometry is the study of differentiable manifolds equipped with nondegenerate, symmetric 2-tensors (called metric tensors).
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Symplectic geometry has a number of similarities with and differences from Riemannian geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Unlike in the Riemannian case, symplectic manifolds have no local invariants such as curvature.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] This is a consequence of Darboux's theorem which states that a neighborhood of any point of a 2*n*-dimensional symplectic manifold is isomorphic to the standard symplectic structure on an open set of $\mathbb {R} ^{2n}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Another difference with Riemannian geometry is that not every differentiable manifold can admit a symplectic form; there are certain topological restrictions.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] For example, every symplectic manifold is even-dimensional and orientable.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Additionally, if *M* is a closed symplectic manifold, then the 2nd de Rham cohomology group *H*2(*M*) is nontrivial (even more - every even-dimensional cohomology group is nontrivial); this implies, for example, that the only *n*-sphere that admits a symplectic form is the 2-sphere.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] A parallel that one can draw between the two subjects is the analogy between geodesics in Riemannian geometry and pseudoholomorphic curves in symplectic geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Geodesics are curves of shortest length (locally), while pseudoholomorphic curves are surfaces of minimal area.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Both concepts play a fundamental role in their respective disciplines.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Every Kähler manifold is also a symplectic manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Most symplectic manifolds, one can say, are not Kähler; and so do not have an integrable complex structure compatible with the symplectic form.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Mikhail Gromov, however, made the important observation that symplectic manifolds do admit an abundance of compatible almost complex structures, so that they satisfy all the axioms for a Kähler manifold *except* the requirement that the transition maps be holomorphic.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Gromov used the existence of almost complex structures on symplectic manifolds to develop a theory of pseudoholomorphic curves, which has led to a number of advancements in symplectic topology, including a class of symplectic invariants now known as Gromov–Witten invariants.
[src:hamiltonian-mechanics/symplectic-geometry] Later, using the pseudoholomorphic curve technique Andreas Floer invented another important tool in symplectic geometry known as the Floer homology.
